00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.420
SIMON PAMPENA: So, 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 ...

00:00:04.440 --> 00:00:08.100
OK, two multiplied by itself five times is 32.

00:00:08.420 --> 00:00:13.660
So the opposite of that, is a question: What number multiplied by itself five times gives you 32?

00:00:13.900 --> 00:00:19.460
And the way you express that, is that you go,  is 32 to the fifth.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:21.260
That's the fifth root.

00:00:21.260 --> 00:00:23.560
And that happens to be 2.

00:00:24.420 --> 00:00:29.040
So, because in mathematics, there's some beautiful patterns, there's actually a way

00:00:29.620 --> 00:00:35.540
that you can work out the fifth root of very large numbers in your head very quickly.

00:00:35.540 --> 00:00:38.060
And you don't have to use a lot of computing power, brain power.

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:45.360
So, Brady, if you take any double digit number you like, and multiply by itself

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:46.800
5 times

00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:52.280
and you tell me that number, in English, from left to right,

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:57.360
and I write it down, I will be able to tell you what your original number was.

00:00:58.360 --> 00:00:59.360
OK.

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:07.720
OK, you got a number?

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:08.340
BRADY HARAN: Yeah. SIMON PAMPENA: Is it big?

00:01:08.340 --> 00:01:09.740
BRADY HARAN: Yeah, it's big. You ready?

00:01:09.740 --> 00:01:12.060
It's 79 million — PAMPENA: Wait a minute. —

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:18.340
PAMPENA: 79 million. — HARAN: 235 thousand.

